From: r03_260516_supervisor (window-mode backfill)
Subject: SyntheticBackfiller window mode + supervisor --lookback_days flag

Two changes, one feature:

1. SyntheticBackfiller.backfill() gains an optional lookback_days parameter.
   When provided, switches from gap-fill mode (fetch from MAX(kc_timestamp)
   to now) to window mode (always fetch the last N days, INSERT IGNORE
   dedupes against existing rows). Existing callers (cmd_backfill_synthetic)
   work unchanged — default None preserves gap-fill behavior.

2. cmd_supervisor gains --lookback_days flag (default 35) and passes it
   through to backfill(), guaranteeing the kline_collection table always
   holds the requested minimum coverage window before workers spawn.

The supervisor will now ALWAYS backfill on start — including when data is
already current — because window mode ignores the 30s short-circuit. For
typical operation this means re-fetching the last 35 days every supervisor
restart, with INSERT IGNORE accepting nearly all rows as duplicates. Cost:
one big Bybit fetch (~50k 1m bars across ~50 paginated requests) and a
batch INSERT that mostly no-ops. A few minutes per restart, predictable.

Apply with:
    git apply --check r03_260516_supervisor_window.diff
    git apply r03_260516_supervisor_window.diff

Suggested commit message:
    feat: supervisor ensures N days of kline coverage on every start

    SyntheticBackfiller.backfill() gains window mode (lookback_days param);
    supervisor passes args.lookback_days (default 35) so kline_collection
    is guaranteed to hold the minimum coverage window before workers spawn.
    INSERT IGNORE handles dedup with existing rows.
